#mansw15 @gkissane52 Ken Wissen has got all 1-30 without [ ], floor or ceiling functions. Well done! Now, is concatenation really needed??

RT @gkissane52: @BarryKissane and greatest integer fn is not allowed. Although 8!! = 8√ó6√ó4√ó2 or 9!! = 9√ó7√ó5√ó3√ó1 is allowed. .
@gkissane52 I've been doing it many years, but the keep the digits in order rule is a tougher game. Need a ceiling function too, sometimes
@gkissane52 In fact, I would read 3!! as 720, since I read it as (3!)!. I notice, incidentally, that calculating devices do the same.
@gkissane52 And 1000 must have been even harder ...
@gkissane52 Hmmm. Both these !! are pretty dodgy imho. If you keep digits in correct order, greatest integer function is often needed.
@gkissane52 Out of year order is much much easier, however!
@gkissane52 That gives 23, which I got from 20 + [sqrt(15)], less elegantly. (The challenge was to get 1 to 30.)
@misterwootube @m #mansw15 Ken Wessen has a neat solution for 27 that doesn't involve floor or ceiling functions: 2+0!+(-1+5)! Well done!
#mansw15 Lovely session on the joys of mathematics teaching from Nicky Vanderhout, and participants. Thanks for sharing
@nomad_penguin #mansw. Hmmm. It's an arbitrary choice of course, but I would choose to not allow that sort of concatenation. I didn't needit
@nomad_penguin #mansw15 Yes. The in order bit is a big problem often. To get all 30 seems necessary to allow concatenation too. Eg 20 or 15.
#mansw15 Josephus problem and links to binary notation sounds really interesting. Description on Wikipedia. Thanks Mike Clapper.
#mansw15 Love the Interactivate tesselations app Mike Clapper showed. DIY Escher!
@misterwootube #mansw15 Well done! I needed greatest integer functions for some, so floor and ceiling functions ok! Thanks!
#MANSW15 Updating the problem: a colleague found (2+0!+1)!+5=29, using 2015 digits in order. Now only 27 is missing to get 1 to 30.
#mansw15 Targetted teaching! Brilliant talk from Di Siemon! Shame she didn't have more time ...
#mansw15 Teachers need to think about how students understand, not how they explain. Brilliant observation by year 9 student from Di Siemon
#mansw15 Importance of maths teachers having their own room highlighted beautifully by Di Siemon. Example of materials being available.
#mansw15 "Success is crucial to engagement". And of course to disengagement. A good reminder from Di Siemon
#mansw15 Surely the research on streaming is among the least implemented in schools. A common practice, known to fail, as Di Siemon said.

#mansw15. Another three: [20/15]=1, where [ ] is the greatest integer function. And 2^0/1^5=1, (2^0)^(1^5)=1, similar to a previous one.
#mansw15. Four ways to get 1 from 2, 0, 1 and 5 are  2x0.1x5 =1, (.2+0x1)5=1, (2+0+1)!-5=1, 2^0x1^5=1. What other ways are there?
